THOUGHT: The assertion occurs because TTI validates shuffle masks assuming indices are within [0, 2*NumOpElts). In this case, the mask indices (4,7) exceed 2*NumOpElts when NumOpElts is inferred incorrectly. To make VectorCombine robust, add an early guard in foldShuffleOfSelects to verify all mask elements are either -1 (poison) or in-bounds of 2*NumOpElts based on the source operand vector element count. If not, bail out before calling TTI.getShuffleCost, preventing the crash without altering transform behavior.

```bash
sed -n '2038,2052p' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp && sed -i '2045a\  auto *Op0VecTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(I.getOperand(0)->getType());
  auto *Op1VecTy = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(I.getOperand(1)->getType());
  if (!Op0VecTy || !Op1VecTy || Op0VecTy != Op1VecTy)
    return false;
  unsigned NumOpElts = Op0VecTy->getNumElements();
  if (!llvm::all_of(Mask, [NumOpElts](int M) { return M == -1 || (M >= 0 && M < (int)(NumOpElts * 2)); }))
    return false;' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp && /llvm-autofix/build/llvm-build/130250/bin/opt /tmp/test.ll -passes=vector-combine -S -mtriple=x86_64-- -mcpu=x86-64-v2
```

